ace." In this biography Sharon M. Harris steers away from a simplistic view and showcases Walker as a Medal of Honor recipient, examining her work as an activist, author, and Civil War surgeon, along with the many nineteenth-century issues she championed:political, social, medical, and legal reforms, abolition, temperance, gender equality, U.S. imperialism, and the New Woman. Rich in research and keyed to a new generation, Dr. Mary Walker captures its subject's articulate political voice, public self, and the realities of an individual whose ardent beliefs in justice helped shape the radical politics of her time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aPhysicianszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aRadicalszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen physicianszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh  aDr. Mary Walker, suffragist, pants wearer, literature, feminist studies, gender studies, history, psychology, sociology, London Anglo-American Times, reporter, biography, Sharon M. Harris, Medal of Honor recipient, activist, author, Civil War surgeon, nineteenth-century issues, political reform, social reform, medical reform, legal reform, abolition, temperance, gender equality, U.S. imperialism, New Woman, research-rich, articulate political voice, public self, radical politics, justice, social activism, women's rights, Civil War history, gender roles, progressive movements, historical biography, women's suffrage, gender dynamics, social justice, feminist activism, historical significance, progressive era, feminist icon.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081354819740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813548197423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813548197/o